1728":"1728","23 NOV 1745":"23 November 1745","1738":"1738","1735":"1735","Evangelisch,Freckenfeld,Pfalz,Bavaria":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maria","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Maria  , of German origin but now also moderately popular in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaretha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Maria Margaretha had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Jacob Nagel."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1728–1792":"1728–1792","1730–Female":"1730–Surnud","1735–Male":"1735–Surnud","1738–Male":"1738–Surnud","1745–Female":"1745–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1745":"1745","07 JUL 1730":"7. juuli 1730","19 JUL 1738":"19. juuli 1738","1730":"1730","09 NOV 1735":"9. november 1735","1792":"1792","1728":"1728","23 NOV 1745":"23. november 1745","1738":"1738","1735":"1735","Evangelisch,Freckenfeld,Pfalz,Bavaria":"Pfalz, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1728–1792":"1728–1792","1730–Female":"1730–Kuollut","1735–Male":"1735–Kuollut","1738–Male":"1738–Kuollut","1745–Female":"1745–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1745":"1745","07 JUL 1730":"7. heinäkuuta 1730","19 JUL 1738":"19. heinäkuuta 1738","1730":"1730","09 NOV 1735":"9. marraskuuta 1735","1792":"1792","1728":"1728","23 NOV 1745":"23. marraskuuta 1745","1738":"1738","1735":"1735","Evangelisch,Freckenfeld,Pfalz,Bavaria":"Pfalz, Bayern, Saksa"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1728–1792":"1728–1792","1730–Female":"1730–Décédée","1735–Male":"1735–Décédé","1738–Male":"1738–Décédé","1745–Female":"1745–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1745":"1745","07 JUL 1730":"